### Model Interpretation Summary

After all models are evaluated on the test set, a written summary is produced comparing their relative performance. The summary addresses:

- Which model achieved superior performance, and on which metrics
- Whether the performance difference is meaningful given the dataset size and research context
- Trade-offs between model interpretability (Logistic Regression, Linear Regression) and predictive power (Random Forest, XGBoost)
- Whether SMOTE or class weighting improved minority-class recall without sacrificing overall F1-Score
- Practical implications for HBCU student success platform recommendations

> **Example Summary (template):**
> *The Random Forest Classifier outperformed Logistic Regression on F1-Score (0.78 vs. 0.71) and Recall for the minority class (0.74 vs. 0.62), suggesting it better captures the non-linear relationships between endowment per student, platform adoption, and retention outcomes. However, Logistic Regression remains preferable for institutional reporting due to its coefficient interpretability. For regression, XGBoost produced a lower RMSE (4.21 vs. 6.38) and higher R² (0.81 vs. 0.63) compared to Linear Regression, indicating that graduation rate is better explained by non-linear feature interactions.*

